solutions.content:
This is a beautiful solution, which took me some time to think. This solution is very easy to understand with the O(N) solution. 
I have used the 2-pointer technique to solve this question.
**Code Implementation:**
Let us consider the Eg. " . L . R . . . L R . . L . . "
So, we will iterate the string twice,
In first iteration, we iterate from left to right, Therefore, when we encounter 'R',  that means it will make the next domino fall towards right (If it was a ' . ').
Let us use an array to store the count of dominoes which may fall towards right,
After first Iteration, the 'r' array will be 
 .  L  .  R  .  .  .  L R  .  .  L  .  . 
0  0 0 0  1 2 3 0 0  1 2 0  0 0

Now, in our second iteration, we travel the string from right to left, therefore, we mark all the ' . 's if they have a tendency to fall towards left
 .  L  .  R  .  .  .  L R  .  .  L  .  . 
1  0 0 0  3 2 1 0 0  2 1 0  0 0

So, now, we have 2 arrays and we can compare them to get the effective direction of fall.
The conditions are, 
* If a domino doesnt fall towards Left (l[i] == 0), but falls towards Right (r[i] > 0) then it has only one direction hence it will fall towards Right, and vice versa.
* If we notice that both l[i] && r[i] are zero then that means it was already assigned a direction which we can get from the input string.
* If l[i] && r[i] have same non zero value for L and R, that means it has it its neighbouring domino falling towards it, that means it won't fall, hence we will assign ' . ' to this.
* And the last case is, if l[i] > r[i] and both are non zero, then we assign the direction R(minimum value of l[i] and r[i] get the direction.)

Happy Coding!

```
class Solution {
public:
    Solution(){
        ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
        cin.tie(NULL); cout.tie(NULL);
    }
    string pushDominoes(string s){
        int n = s.length();
        vector<int> l(n, 0), r(n, 0);
        char prev = '.';
        int count = 1;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            if(s[i] == 'R'){
                prev = 'R';
                count = 1;
                continue;
            }
            else if(s[i] == 'L') prev = 'L';
            if(prev == 'R' && s[i] == '.') r[i] = count++;
        }
        prev = '.';
        count = 1;
        for(int i=n-1; i>=0; i--){
            if(s[i] == 'L'){
                prev = 'L';
                count = 1;
                continue;
            }
            else if(s[i] == 'R') prev = 'R';
            if(prev == 'L' && s[i] == '.') l[i] = count++;
        }
        string ans = "";
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            if(!l[i] && !r[i]) ans += s[i];
            else if(!l[i]) ans += 'R';
            else if(!r[i]) ans += 'L';
            else if(l[i] == r[i]) ans += '.';
            else if(l[i] > r[i]) ans += 'R';
            else ans += 'L';
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

