The n^2 solution to this problem is easy but it was difficult for me to find a way to not do so much repeated work. I came up with this idea: 
Maintain the position of the closest domino pointing RIGHT. If we encounter a left domino along the way, the position of the closest domino pointing right is INFINITY because the left cancels it out.

Look for the closest domino pointing LEFT. We do this by iterating ahead of our current position. If there is a right domino along the way, the position of the closest domino opint left is INFINITY because the right cancels it out.
Important: We only need to redo this step if closestLeft is BEHIND our current position, because if the closestLeft for i = 3 is index 9, it will also be the closest left for indices 4...8.

Now we know the positions of our closest right and left dominos. So for any given '.', we just need to check the absolute distance from the closestLeft or closestRight domino and set it to that one. If they are equidistant, then we do not change the '.'.

```
    string pushDominoes(string d) {
        const int INF = 10e5;
        int closestLeft = INF; // in front
        int closestRight = INF; // behind
        int j = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < d.length(); i++){
            if(closestLeft <= i || (j <= i && closestLeft == INF)){ // find the closest left domino if it exists 
                j = i;
                while(j < d.length()){ // dont redo calculation if closestleft is >= i because the answer remains the same
                        // do redo if closestleft <= i OR j <= i AND closestLeft = infinity
                        if(d[j] == 'L'){
                            closestLeft = j;
                            break;
                        }
                        if(d[j] == 'R'){
                            closestLeft = INF;
                            break;
                        }
                        j++;
                    }
            }
            if(closestLeft < i) closestLeft = INF; // closestLeft does not exist if it's behind the domino because it can never push it

            if(d[i] == 'R') closestRight = i; // do this before checking if it's a '.' because it might mistakenly update it
            else if(d[i] == 'L') closestRight = INF;

            if(d[i] == '.'){
                if(abs(closestLeft-i) < abs(closestRight-i)) d[i] = 'L'; // left is closer in absolute distance so it will reach this domino first
                else if(abs(closestLeft-i) > abs(closestRight-i)) d[i] = 'R'; // right is closer in absolute distance so it will reach this domino first 
            }
        }
        return d;
    }

