Once you find how every vowel can be generated depending on existing vowels, it could be straightforward to get this formula:

`a` = `e` + `i` + `u`
`e` = `a` + `i`
`i` = `e` + `o`
`o` = `i`
`u` = `i` + `o`

Get new result based on previous step, which is a classic DP problem.

**Recursive:**
```
class Solution {
    int mod = 1000000007;
    public int countVowelPermutation(int n) {
        long sum = 0;
        long[] v = new long[]{1, 1, 1, 1, 1}; // a-0, e-1, i-2, o-3, u-4
        for (long i : iterate(v, n - 1)) 
            sum = (sum + i) % mod;
        return (int) sum;
    }

    public long[] iterate(long[] v, int n) {
        if (n == 0) return v;
        long[] v1 = new long[5];
        v1[0] = (v[1] + v[2] + v[4]) % mod;
        v1[1] = (v[0] + v[2]) % mod;
        v1[2] = (v[1] + v[3]) % mod;
        v1[3] = v[2];
        v1[4] = (v[2] + v[3]) % mod;
        return iterate(v1, n - 1);
    }
}
```

**Iterative:**
```
public int countVowelPermutation(int n) {
    int mod = 1000000007;
    long sum = 0;
    long[] v = new long[]{1, 1, 1, 1, 1}; // a-0, e-1, i-2, o-3, u-4
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        long[] v1 = new long[5];
        v1[0] = (v[1] + v[2] + v[4]) % mod;
        v1[1] = (v[0] + v[2]) % mod;
        v1[2] = (v[1] + v[3]) % mod;
        v1[3] = v[2];
        v1[4] = (v[2] + v[3]) % mod;
        v = v1;
    }
    for (long i : v) 
        sum = (sum + i) % mod;
    return (int) sum;
}
```

