solutions.content:
The problem is tricky because it might tempt you to do some backtracking DFS magic, but given the possible size of `n`, you might not exactly be set for success with this approach.

A better one comes from storing previous results - one from each letter: we will build our `dp` matrix in this guise, with the first index (the row one) representing the length of the current permutation minus `1` (since we will use a `0` indexed matrix) and the second one (the column) representing the last number in it (normalising the `"aeiou"` range into a `0 - 4` one), so for example `dp[7][3]` will represent all the permutations of `8` characters we can have terminating with the letter `o`.

We are then going to create a `dp` matrix with `n` rows and `5` columns and set the very first column values all to `1` (ie: using only one number, you can have only one combination).

Looping `n - 1` times, we can iteratively compute all the other values, with the following approach, according to the specs:
* `prev` is always going to be the current index minus `1`;
* `'a'` can only follow `'e'`, `'i'` and `'u'`, so we will have that `dp[i][0] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][1] + dp[prev][2] + dp[prev][4])`;
* `'e'` can only follow `'a'`, and `'i'`, so we will have that `dp[i][1] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][0] + dp[prev][2])`;
* `'i'` can only follow `'e'`, and `'o'`, so we will have that `dp[i][2] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][1] + dp[prev][3])`;
* `'o'` can only follow `'i'`, so we will have that `dp[i][3] = dp[prev][2]` (notice we do not even need to call `moduloReduce` for this one);
* `'u'` can only follow `'i'` and `'o'`, so we will have that `dp[i][4] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][2] + dp[prev][3])`.

Now, a few words on `moduloReduce`: this function takes a number `n` and while it is `>= modVal`, it just subtract this value from `n` - that is actually cheaper ([in this case](https://leetcode.com/problems/count-vowels-permutation/discuss/1315096/C++-DP-Solution-Explained-100-Time-~98-Space/997684)) than calling the modulo operator on it all the time!

Once done, we sum the partial results of the last column, again calling `moduloReduce` on said sum and we are done :)

The code:

```cpp
static constexpr int modVal = 1000000007;

class Solution {
    long moduloReduce(long n) {
        while (n > modVal) n -= modVal;
        return n;
    }
public:
    int countVowelPermutation(int n) {
        long dp[n][5];
        // initialising dp
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) dp[0][i] = 1;
        // computing all the following steps
        for (int i = 1, prev = 0; i < n; i++) {
            // case 'a' - which can only follow 'e', 'i' and 'u':
            dp[i][0] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][1] + dp[prev][2] + dp[prev][4]);
            // case 'e' - which can only follow 'a' and 'i':
            dp[i][1] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][0] + dp[prev][2]);
            // case 'i' - which can only follow 'e' and 'o':
            dp[i][2] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][1] + dp[prev][3]);
            // case 'o' - which can only follow 'i':
            dp[i][3] = dp[prev][2];
            // case 'u' - which can only follow 'i' and 'o':
            dp[i][4] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][2] + dp[prev][3]);
            // updating prev
            prev = i;
        }
        return moduloReduce(dp[--n][0] + dp[n][1] + dp[n][2] + dp[n][3] + dp[n][4]);
    }
};
```

But, wait a moment: do we really need `n` rows in our matrix?

Probably not, since we are always advancing to one row, using the previous one.

Then we can refactor and save a lot more memory 🎉 :

```cpp
static constexpr int modVal = 1000000007;

class Solution {
    long moduloReduce(long n) {
        while (n > modVal) n -= modVal;
        return n;
    }
public:
    int countVowelPermutation(int n) {
        long dp[2][5];
        int prev = 0;
        // initialising dp
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) dp[0][i] = 1;
        // computing all the following steps
        for (int i = 1, curr = 1; i < n; i++) {
            // case 'a' - which can only follow 'e', 'i' and 'u':
            dp[curr][0] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][1] + dp[prev][2] + dp[prev][4]);
            // case 'e' - which can only follow 'a' and 'i':
            dp[curr][1] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][0] + dp[prev][2]);
            // case 'i' - which can only follow 'e' and 'o':
            dp[curr][2] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][1] + dp[prev][3]);
            // case 'o' - which can only follow 'i':
            dp[curr][3] = dp[prev][2];
            // case 'u' - which can only follow 'i' and 'o':
            dp[curr][4] = moduloReduce(dp[prev][2] + dp[prev][3]);
            // updating prev and curr
            prev = curr;
            curr = !curr;
        }
        return moduloReduce(dp[prev][0] + dp[prev][1] + dp[prev][2] + dp[prev][3] + dp[prev][4]);
    }
};
```

