solutions.content:
Well, First think of the **smallest case possible**, `(n == 1)` *In this case the answer is clearly 5*  *('a', 'e', 'i', 'o', 'u')*. Then, think of the number of ways you can make ans for `( n == 2 ) `, *By adding characters at the end of all the answer strings in (n == 1) by following the rules. Right?*

To consider all the possibilities I have made an array `"data"` which stores all the eligible characters we can append to each of the current string.

So, we have to figure out the ans for 'n' and have only five type of strings possible at each level (**ending with all the five characters**) hence the **dp** array is of dimensions `( n + 1 ) * 5`.

*Now, you can go through the code to understand the problem and its approach completely.*


```
class Solution {
    public int countVowelPermutation(int n) {
        long[][] dp = new long[n+1][5];
		// Filling the dp array for base case (i.e, n == 1)
        for(int i=0; i<5; i++){
            dp[1][i] = 1;
        }

		// Considering  a = 0, e = 1, i = 2, o = 3 and u  = 4 ( for the representation of their indices )
		// Filling the data array with the characters we can append after the respective character
        int[][] data = {{1}, {0, 2}, {0, 1, 3, 4}, {2, 4}, {0}};
        int M = (int)1e9+7;

        for(int i=2; i<=n; i++){
		// we started forming the ans from n = 2 case

            for(int j=0; j<5; j++){
			// traversing all the columns of previous row and adding in the current one

                for(int k=0; k<data[j].length; k++){
				// We have to add to all those characters which can be appended by the previous end characters. 
				//So, the number of strings ending with 'e's can be formed by appending after all the previously ending with 'a' strings
				// Here, the mod has also been taken to prevent overflow
				// data[j][k] let'say for j=0 will represent the index of 'e' (1). And we add the number of 'a's ( dp[ i - 1 ][ j ] ) to it.

                    dp[i][data[j][k]] = (dp[i][data[j][k]] + dp[i-1][j])%M;
                }
            }
        }

		// At the end the sum of all the strings (ending with the respective character) is our answer for all the strings of length 'n'
        long sum = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<5; i++){
            sum =(sum + dp[n][i])%M;
        }
        return (int)sum;
    }
}
```

