This solution can be easier to understand if one is familiar with the memoization(top-down) technique used to solve the standard fibonacci series problem with dp.

I'll try to explain with an analogical visualizaion...

```
length             string ending at vowel
     n                          a
                             /  |  \
                            /   |   \
                           /    |    \
     n-1                  e     i     u
                         / \   / \   / \
     n-2                a   i e   o i   o
     .                       
     .
     . and so on
```

I hope this clearly shows the overlapping sub-problems(the 2 **i**'s and 2 **o**'s at length n-2) that are being encountered and why dp is necessary to avoid repition of calculating same sub-problem again and again!

```
class Solution {

    static int[][] dp;
    static int mod = 1000000007;

    public int countVowelPermutation(int n) {

        /*  a -> 0
            e -> 1
            i -> 2
            o -> 3
            u -> 4   */

        dp = new int[5][n+1]; // dp array stores the no. of strings of length 'n' ending at i-th vowel 

        for(int i=0; i<5; i++)
                dp[i][1] = 1; // base cases where for n = 1, each character itself is a valid string


        // prefix array stores 1 at all the j-th indexes where i-th vowel is preceeded by j-th vowel

        int[][] prefix = {{-1, 1, 1, -1, 1},   //a preceeded by e,i,u (1,2,4)...therefore prefix[0][1] = prefix[0][2] = prefix[0][4] = 1
                          {1, -1, 1, -1, -1},  //e preceeded by a,i (0,2)
                          {-1, 1, -1, 1, -1},  //i preceeded by e,o (1,3)
                          {-1, -1, 1, -1, -1}, //o preceeded by i (2)
                          {-1, -1, 1, 1, -1}}; //u preceeded by i,0 (2,3)



        for(int i=0; i<5; i++){
            digDown(i, n, prefix); // the actual solution phase...finding all the strings ending at each vowel with length 'n'
        }

        int sum = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<5; i++){
            sum = (sum + dp[i][n]%mod)%mod; // calculating the answer...adding up the total strings ending at each vowel
        }

        return sum;

    }

    public void digDown(int c, int n, int[][] prefix){
        // here c is the index of current vowel and n is the current lenght of string into consideration

        if(n == 1) return; // remember the base cases mentioned earlier!

        for(int i=0; i<5; i++){

            if(prefix[c][i] == 1){ // i.e. if the vowel 'c' is preceeded by vowel 'i' we proceed further

                if(dp[i][n-1] == 0) digDown(i, n-1, prefix); // if the value(i.e. the no. of strings) is not yet calculated for string ending at 
                                                             // vowel i of length 'n-1'...we call the recursive function to find that out

                dp[c][n] = (dp[c][n]%mod + dp[i][n-1]%mod)%mod; // finally adding the values from vaild predecessor vowel
            }
        }        
    }
}
```

