**DP: Linear calculation**

Let dp[L][a] represent the number of strings of length ```L``` ending with ```a``` (same thing goes for other characters), then as per the rules given in the problem, we have the following recurrence relations:

dp[L+1][a] = dp[L][e] + dp[L][i] + dp[L][u]       // because ```a``` can come after ```e```, ```i``` and ```u``` only
dp[L+1][e] = dp[L][a] + dp[L][i]
dp[L+1][i] = dp[L][e] + dp[L][o]
dp[L+1][o] = dp[L][i]
dp[L+1][u] = dp[L][i] + dp[L][o]

As values for dp[L+1] depends only on dp[L] values, we can just maintain the last set of values instead of full dp table thereby reducing space.

```
// 8 ms. 92.46%
class Solution {
    public int countVowelPermutation(int n) {
        long A = 1, E = 1, I = 1, O = 1, U = 1, MOD = 1_000_000_007;
        while(--n > 0) {
            long a = A, e = E, i = I, o = O, u = U;
            A = (e + i + u) % MOD;
            E = (a + i) % MOD;
            I = (e + o) % MOD;
            O = i;
            U = (i + o) % MOD;
        }
        return (int) ((A + E + I + O + U) % MOD);
    }
}
```

Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(1)

**DP: Logarithmic calculation using matrix multiplication**
************
We can speed up calculation of higher terms of linear recurrence relations using matrix multiplication. Approach goes like this:

Say, we have a function f which is recursively defined like this:

f(i) = c(i-1) * f(i-1) + c(i-2) * f(i-2) + ... + c(i-k) * f(i-k)

where c(i-1), c(i-2) ... c(i-k) are some constant values which represent the coefficients of corresponding terms. Since f depends on last k terms, we'd be given its first k values (or base case), in other words, f(0), f(1), ... f(k-1) are known.

Now, we define two matrices, F(i) and C.

F(i) is a 1 x k matrix = [ f(i) f(i-1) ... f(i-k+1) ]
Similarly, F(i-1) = [ f(i-1) f(i-2) ... f(i-k) ]

C is a k x k matrix = [ c(i-1) 1 0 ... 0 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;[ c(i-2) 0 1 ... 0 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;[ c(i-3) 0 0 ... 0 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;...
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;[ c(i-k+1) 0 0 ... 1 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;[ c(i-k) 0 0 ... 0 ]

First column has all the coefficients. Second column has a 1 in first row, all other elements are zero. Third column has a 1 in second row, all other elements are zero. And so on for the remaining columns.

Defining F and C this way ensures that:
[ f(i) f(i-1) ... f(i-k+1) ] = [ f(i-1) f(i-2) ... f(i-k) ] * [ c(i-1) 1 0 ... 0 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;[ c(i-2) 0 1 ... 0 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp; [ c(i-3) 0 0 ... 0 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;...
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;[ c(i-k+1) 0 0 ... 1 ]
&nbsp; &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;[ c(i-k) 0 0 ... 0 ]

i.e. F(i) = F(i-1) * C
So to get F(i+1),
F(i+1) = F(i) * C = F(i-1) * C * C = F(i-1) * C<sup>2</sup>
Similarly, to get F(n),
F(n) = F(n-1) * C = F(n-2) * C<sup>2</sup> = ... = F(k-1) * C<sup>n-k+1</sup>

Calculating C<sup>p</sup> takes O(log p) iterations using [exponentiation by squaring](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation_by_squaring). Since all multiplications are of k x k matrices, it takes O(k<sup>3</sup>) time for each.

So, overall time complexity to calculate f(n) using this approach is O(k<sup>3</sup> log (n - k + 1)). Since k is generally much smaller compared to n, this is much faster than O(n).

************
Coming to this problem, our matrix equation looks like this:

[ dp[L+1][a]  dp[L+1][e] dp[L+1][i] dp[L+1][o] dp[L+1] [u] ] = [ dp[L][a]  dp[L][e] dp[L][i] dp[L][o] dp[L] [u] ] * [ 0 1 0 0 0 ]
