The simplest way to approach this problem is by using dynamic programming. The Hint 2 given in the description gives away the actual way to go. 
"**Let dp[i][j] be the number of strings of length i that ends with the j-th vowel.**"

We will initialize a 2-D matrix of size  n * 5 where n is the length of strings and 5 , which is the number of vowels. 

dp[i][j] will denote the number of strings of length "i" which end with "jth vowel". Ex: dp[0][1] = 1 --> number of strings of length 1 which end with 2nd vowel - e 

**Note that I am using zero based indexing here.**

The first row will be all 1s as there can exactly 1 possible combination of all vowels. 

We will follow the set of rules given and update the rows till we reach the n th row. 

As the sum will be large, we will use mod(10 power 9 + 7).

At the end, we will calculate the mod of sum of elements of the nth row and return.

```
int countVowelPermutation(int n) {
        int count = 0;
        vector<vector<long long int>> dp(n, vector<long long int> (5, 0));
        for(int i=0;i<5;++i)
            dp[0][i] = 1;

        for(int i=0;i<n-1;++i){
            for(int j=0;j<5;++j){
                switch(j){
                    case 0:
                        {
                            dp[i+1][1] = (dp[i][j] + dp[i+1][1])%mod ;
                            break;
                        }
                    case 1:
                        {
                            dp[i+1][0] = (dp[i][j] + dp[i+1][0])%mod;
                            dp[i+1][2] = (dp[i][j] + dp[i+1][2])%mod;
                            break;
                        }
                    case 2:
                        {
                            dp[i+1][0] = (dp[i][j]+dp[i+1][0])%mod;
                            dp[i+1][1] = (dp[i][j]+dp[i+1][1])%mod;
                            dp[i+1][3] = (dp[i][j]+dp[i+1][3])%mod;
                            dp[i+1][4] = (dp[i][j]+dp[i+1][4])%mod;
                            break;
                        }
                    case 3:
                        {
                            dp[i+1][2] = (dp[i][j]+dp[i+1][2])%mod;
                            dp[i+1][4] = (dp[i][j]+dp[i+1][4])%mod;
                            break;
                        }
                    case 4:
                        {
                            dp[i+1][0] = (dp[i][j]+dp[i+1][0])%mod;
                            break;
                        }
                }

            }
        }

    for(int i = 0; i < 5; ++i){
        count = (dp[n-1][i] + count)%mod;
    }
    return count;
}
```

